Jupiter unfolds the further developments of the play.

I suspect that this scene, which might be omitted without loss, is not genuine. In fact all the ‘ explanatory ’ parts of the play seem to be late, and by the same hand as the Pro· logue. If this be so, it is probably rash to try and emend the metrica] corruptions. For, as I have said before, I cannot assent to Ritschl’s view that the writers of these parts fully attained to Plautus’s art. Thus the very difficult question arises, How far did they succeed in attaining to it, in what instances fall short of it? In my Critical Notes I have, how· ever, treated the scene as if it were Plautine.
